Small Business InsightsTM (SBI) are built around a suite of indicators derived from Xeros data reflecting trends in the small business economy. The premise is that the accounting data held by Xero, given its volume and detail, serves as a reliable source for deriving aggregate indicators that capture important aspects of the performance of the small business economy and therefore will be a valuable source of information for policy makers, industry groups, and even individual small businesses.

This document provides background information on the design and production of SBI metrics with the purpose of enabling users to interpret the metrics appropriately and to understand their limitations.

General Overview

SBI metrics are similar to official statistics in that they seek to say something relevant about the behavior or attributes of a bigger population in a quantitative form. The value and usefulness of such metrics (or statistics) depend on the degree to which they are successful in capturing something true about the target population.

Internal relevance

SBI metrics are derived from the data that is generated by customers on the Xero accounting platform. For this reason, the SBI metrics are naturally expected to tap into at least the behavior of businesses that are represented on Xero. Creating a metric that is internally relevant is less of a challenge as the sources of error are fewer. After all, all aspects of metric design and derivation are under control, fewer assumptions are made, and therefore the metric output can be more easily claimed to speak the truth about businesses on Xero.

External relevance

Xeros customers are understood to be predominantly small businesses. They are, of course, only a subset of all small businesses in existence, and in turn those small businesses are just a subset of all businesses in any given economy. Given the size of Xeros customer base in the AU/NZ/UK markets, it is quite natural to expect that a metric derived from Xero data may actually reflect broader trends beyond the population of Xero businesses. Whether an SBI metric works well as an indicator for a broader population, such as the small business sector in a particular country overall, is more challenging to assess.

For one thing, the small businesses on Xero are self-selected and so is the data that they generate through their business transactions. What this means is that we have little control over the data generation mechanisms in a statistical sense: Xero does not pick its customers, nor does it tell them what accounting information they should record. The data we deal with is organically generated for a distinct primary purpose. The production of SBI metrics is only a secondary purpose for this data. In contrast, many official statistics traditionally rely on data that is collected for the primary purpose of statistical analysis and employ some form of sampling, where they carefully design the selection mechanism (often seeking randomness) in an effort to avoid systematic bias that would undermine the representativeness of the statistics produced.

Does the organic nature of Xeros data mean that the aggregate metrics derived from it will bear no external relevance? No, not at all. Our raw data may be reasonably representative of a broader small business population, but not by design. Our sample (or rather group) sizes are substantial, especially compared to the sample sizes acquired for official statistics. While size does matter, correspondence between the characteristics of the samples and the broader population is also very important. SBI metrics have strong external relevance if we trust the assumption that the small businesses on Xero are very similar in composition and business behavior to all those not represented on Xero. In the future, the SBI team will seek to investigate systematically how strongly this assumption holds. Unfortunately, this poses a sizeable challenge as information about the true nature of the greater small business population is limited, especially in a special aspect like getting paid, where our data may be quite unique. For the time being, we rely on qualitative sanity checks on how robust SBI metrics are from an external relevance point of view.

Error framework

How well a certain measure performs in terms of capturing something useful and valuable about reality can be assessed by comparing the ideal (often elusive) measure and the actual measure one can practically produce. Perfect alignment is almost never possible, so it is important to be aware of the sources of error and their implications. For SBI, we evaluate the design of our metrics in terms of the following error framework[1].

We can separate the sources of error into two streams. Measurement concerns the conceptual soundness of the measures, whereas representation concerns how successful we are in terms of collecting that information on the population of interest. In the following, we provide a high level evaluation of each SBI metric in terms of these categories. We describe how the actual SBI measures relate to what could be understood as ideal and we highlight critical differences (marked red), potential issues (amber), and good alignment (green) in the process of operationalising the measures.

Cloud Adoption

Modern business increasingly relies on cloud-based computing and data solutions, which represent steps toward more efficient and cost-effective business operations. The SBI Cloud Adoption metric seeks to tap into these trends by looking into patterns of adoption among its customer base.

Measurement[2]
Target concept the degree of reliance on cloud-based business applications
Validity error cloud accounting is just one segment of potential cloud-based business applications
Target measure the movement in the number of small businesses relying on Xero as their accounting platform
Measurement error reducing subtle aspects of adoption to being a paying customer as an indicator of adoption. A small business may not map to a single org in a one-to-one fashion.
Obtained measure change in the volume of net org sign-ups (sign-ups - deletes) in a given month

Representation[3]
Target set all small businesses adopting some kind of cloud accounting solution
Frame error Xero customers represent a self-selected subset from the broader set of small businesses. The characteristics of the subset may not be in alignment with the broader population, introducing potential bias.
Accessible set small businesses signing up on Xero
Selection error full enumeration of orgs is possible, selection criteria for orgs are straightforward.
Accessed set all subscribing orgs on Xero (meeting the criteria of selection)

Unit of Analysis

  • organisation (aka org) as the basic concept in the Xero data architecture representing a business entity for which accounting records are held.

Data source

  • XeroCard (Xeros customer database)

Selection logic

Level Criterion Comment
Data level Use most recent version of available data
Business entity level Select every org that are:
is not in trial mode paying customer as real adopter
uses the Business Edition of Xero
is not a practice endusers only
is not a partner endusers only
is in the market of interest (e.g. UK, NZ, AU) target market only
signs up or deletes in the period of interest target period only
Transaction level N/A

Aggregation logic

Step Description
1. Count the number of orgs that sign up in each industry.
2. Count the number of orgs that get deleted in each industry.
3. Calculate net sign-up by differencing (1) and (2) in each industry.
4. Calculate the number of active Xero orgs in each industry by adding (3) to (4) of the previous period

Metric calculation

Metric Description Unit
Industry ranking based on speed
  1. Calculate YoY growth rate by dividing current periods number of active orgs by that of the same period last year.
  2. Rank all industries based on their respective growth rate by assigning #1 to the one with the highest growth rate.
 rank
Industry ranking based on volume
  1. Calculate YoY growth volume by differencing current periods number of active orgs and that of the same period last year.
  2. Rank all industries based on their respective growth volume by assigning #1 to the one with the highest growth volume.
 rank
Top 5 Industries
  1. Calculate YoY growth volume by differencing current periods number of active orgs and that of the same period last year.
  2. Select the 5 industries that saw the highest growth volume and combine their volumes
  3. Calculate the share of each of the 5 industries in their combined growth volume.
 % proportion

Visualisation

Metric Description
Industry ranking based on speed Bump chart showing rank changes over time
Industry ranking based on volume Bump chart showing rank changes over time
Top 5 Industries Pie chart

Hiring People

In many economies, small businesses play a vital role in creating jobs, often employing the greatest chunk of the labour force. The SBI Hiring People metric taps into hiring trends as reflected in payroll data hosted on Xero.

Measurement
Target concept the relative change in the number of people employed in the small business sector
Validity error direct correspondence between target concept and target measure
Target measure the relative change in the number of people employed by small businesses that are on Xero
Measurement error minimal, being formally paid corresponds directly to being employed.
Obtained measure the relative change in the number of unique payslips/payees processed by orgs using Xero Payroll

Representation
Target set payroll records of all small businesses that employ people
Frame error Xero customers represent a self-selected subset from the broader set of small businesses. The characteristics of the subset may not be in alignment with the broader population, introducing potential bias.
Not all Xero customers use the Payroll module.
Xero Payroll users may not record all payroll information accurately and in a timely manner.
Accessible set payroll records of all small businesses using Xero Payroll
Selection error Due to the 12-month rule we miss out on the true hiring behavior of users recently signing up to Xero Payroll.
Old Xero Payroll customers adding previously unregistered but existing employees to payroll is accounted as an increase in employment.
Going out of business and thus unsubscribing from Xero Payroll is not captured as a decrease in hiring.
Accessed set all payslips/payees processed/paid by orgs using Xero Payroll (meeting the criteria of selection)

Comments on measurement and representation

The Hiring People metric is based on tracking change in the number of payslips generated for unique payees on Xero Payroll as an indicator of hiring activity. However, the number of unique payees in a given time period can change for a number of reasons, not all of which reflecting true changes in actual hiring:

Status [+] Increase [-] Decrease
True & captured An org already using Payroll hires and pays new employee(s) An org already using Payroll lays off employee(s)
True & uncaptured An org that has just started as a business and freshly signed up on Xero Payroll starts to pay its new employee(s) An org lays off its employees and unsubscribes from Xero Payroll
False & uncaptured An existing business just signs up on Xero Payroll and starts to run payroll for its existing employee(s) An org keeps operating with no changes in employment but unsubscribes from Payroll

A reliable employment metric is effective in capturing true changes (set in green) and disregards changes that solely arise from fluctuations in the number of subscribers (set in green). Unfortunately, true hiring events can coincide with changes in subscription status and there is no bullet-proof way of untangling the two. Our approach is to impose a 12-month rule that avoids orgs that have just recently (within 12 months) signed up to use Xero Payroll. This filters out any increase (set in red) induced by new Payroll subscribers, but it comes at a price. It also filters out any true job creation if it happens in the early days of subscription, that is, within the 12-month window.

The selection logic used for Hiring People is asymmetrical in the sense that it tracks changes in the number of payees by way of looking up posted payruns. Discontinuity in payruns (at the org level) is not incorporated in the metric in any way. Similarly to the above, this works for our advantage as decreases in payee numbers occurring due to orgs that simply unsubscribe from Payroll but with no changes in real hiring (set in red on the Decrease side). Again, this comes at a price: the metric does not capture any employment changes resulting from an org unsubscribing and at the same time laying off people.

In summary, the Hiring People metrics will not reflect:

  • hiring behavior of businesses that are in the first 12 months of their Xero Payroll subscription (maybe also in the first 12 months of their existence),
  • hiring behavior of businesses that unsubscribe from Xero Payroll (maybe also going out of business).

Unit of Analysis

  • organisation
  • payslip

Data source

  • Xero Payroll data (payrun, payslip, payee data tables)
  • Organisation details from XeroCard (needed for selection)
  • Custom-generated inclusion table with the list of orgs meeting the revenue criterion

Selection logic

Level Criterion Comment
Data level Use most recent version of available data
Business entity level Select every org that:
is not in trial mode paying customer as real adopter
has min. 13-month presence on Xero Payroll
uses the Business Edition of Xero
is not a practice endusers only
is not a partner endusers only
is in the market of interest (e.g. UK, NZ, AU) target market only
is a Sole Trader/Company/Partnership AU does not include partnerships
meets revenue criterion Under a certain revenue threshold
has a posted payrun in the period of interest
Transaction level Select every payee that
appears in a posted payrun in the period

Aggregation logic

Step Description
1. Select all eligible orgs for the month of interest (T)
2. Select all payruns posted by these orgs
3. Count the number of unique payees in these payruns to get the total for period T
4. Select all payruns posted by the same set of orgs in the preceding month T-1
5. Count the number of unique payees in these payruns to get the total for period T-1

The 13-month rule essentially defines a cohort for a period of two consecutive months. The rate of change in hiring is calculated across these two periods and then the two-month window is moved ahead by one month and the same process is applied for that newly defined cohort.

Metric calculation

Metric Description Unit
Hiring People Growth Rate Calculate MoM growth rate by dividing the number of payees in the current month T by the number of payees in the preceding month T-1 % (MoM)

Note: SBI AU breaks down the Hiring People metric by the type of employment: full time, part time, casual. The piece of data that makes this possible is only available in the AU version of Xero Payroll.

Visualisation

Metric Description
Hiring People Growth Rate Line diagram showing last 12 months

Getting Paid

Small businesses often struggle to get paid in time for the goods they sell or the services they provide. The SBI Getting Paid metric seeks to provide a high level measure of how fast/slow invoices get paid typically and how this speed changes over time.

Measurement
Target concept the degree to which small businesses get paid on time
Validity error Direct correspondence between target concept and target measure
Target measure the number of days it typically takes for an invoice issued by a small business to get paid
Measurement error Invoice information entered by Xero users may contain errors (accuracy, completeness of details), invoices may not be recorded in a timely manner.
Obtained measure the number of days it typically takes for an invoice issued by an org on Xero to get paid

Representation
Target set all invoices issued by small businesses (in a given period)
Frame error Xero customers represent a self-selected subset from the broader set of small businesses. The characteristics of the subset may not be in alignment with the broader population, introducing potential bias.
Invoices entered all invoice information accurately and in a timely manner.
Accessible set all invoices issued by small businesses on Xero
Selection error Due to the 12-month rule we miss out on invoices raised by new orgs
Accessed set all invoices issued by orgs on Xero that meet the selection criteria

Unit of Analysis

  • invoice

Data source

  • Invoice data from Xero product
  • Organisation details from XeroCard (needed for selection)
  • Custom-generated inclusion table with the list of orgs meeting the revenue criterion

Selection logic

Level Criterion Comment
Data level Use most recent version of available data
Business entity level Select every org that:
is not in trial mode paying customer as real adopter
has min. 12-month presence on Xero
uses the Business Edition of Xero
is not a practice endusers only
is not a partner end users only
is in the market of interest (e.g. UK, NZ, AU) target market only
is a Sole Trader/Company/Partnership
meets revenue criterion[4] Under a certain revenue threshold
Transaction level Select every invoice that
is of Account Receivables type
has been fully paid
is not older than 1 year
has a total between 0 and 1 million
date of payment is on or after date of issuing to exclude misrepresented transactions

Aggregation logic

Step Description
1. Select all eligible orgs
2. Select all eligible invoices issued by eligible orgs
3. Calculate the difference between date of full payment and date of issuing for each invoice
4. Calculate the average days-to-pay across all eligible invoices

Metric calculation

Metric Description Unit
Average Days-to-Pay Average days-to-pay (as calculated during aggregation) days

Note: Average Days-To-Pay is displayed for invoices with a 30-day payment term only.

Visualisation

Metric Description
Average Days-to-Pay Line diagram showing last 12 months

Trading Overseas

In the globalising economy lower transaction costs are removing some of the barriers that small businesses must face if they want to be involved in international trade. The Trading Overseas metric taps into the magnitude of import and export trade by small businesses by looking at the value of trade as reflected in invoices. .

Measurement
Target concept the change in the value of export and import by small businesses
Validity error: All legit transactions of overseas trade should be mirrored in accounting records, but not all overseas transactions are conducted in a foreign currency, and not every foreign currency transaction is necessarily an act of overseas trade. It probably picks up the value of goods import/export asymmetrically (imports including the cost of freight, insurance, export likely excluding them).
Target measure the change in the value of foreign currency transactions conducted by small businesses
Measurement error The value of foreign country transactions can be easily selected and their monetary value taken. The value of course may be prone to errors made by users upon recording.
Obtained measure the change in the value of incoming/outgoing invoices recorded by Xero orgs in foreign currencies

Representation
Target set all incoming/outgoing invoices of small businesses made out in foreign currencies (in a given period)
Frame error Xero customers represent a self-selected subset from the broader set of small businesses. The characteristics of the subset may not be in alignment with the broader population, introducing potential bias.
Accessible set all incoming/outgoing invoices entered by Xero orgs in foreign currencies
Selection error Due to the 12-month rule we miss out on invoices belonging to new orgs
Accessed set all foreign currency invoices of Xero orgs that meet the selection criteria

Unit of Analysis

  • organisation
  • invoice

Data source

  • Invoice data from Xero product
  • Organisation details from XeroCard (needed for selection)
  • Custom-generated inclusion table with the list of orgs meeting the revenue criterion

Selection logic

Level Criterion Comment
Data level Use most recent version of available data
Business entity level Select every org that:
is not in trial mode paying customer as real adopter
has min. 12-month presence on Xero
uses the Business Edition of Xero
is not a practice endusers only
is not a partner end users only
is in the market of interest (e.g. UK, NZ, AU) target market only
is a Sole Trader/Company/Partnership
meets revenue criterion Under a certain revenue threshold
Transaction level Select every invoice that
affects a Bank-type account
either related to purchase (import) or sale (export)
under 1 million AUD/NZD/GBP of value
issued in a foreign currency not AUD/NZD/GPB, respectively

Aggregation logic

Step Description
1. Select all eligible orgs in month T.
2. Select all eligible export/import invoices of eligible orgs in T.
3. Calculate the total (base currency) value of export/import invoices for month T.
4. Select all eligible export/import invoices of the same orgs in T+1.
5. Calculate the total (base currency) value of export/import invoices for month T+1.
6. Calculate growth rate in aggregate export/import by dividing T+1 value by T value.

Metric calculation

Metric Description Unit
Import growth rate MoM change in total import value %
Export growth rate MoM change in total export value %

The import and export growth time series currently published on the SBI website are not decomposed to remove seasonal and potential cyclical components. Also, import and export transaction values in the base currency are directly taken from the invoices. These values are calculated by Xero automatically using the foreign exchange rates effective on the day the invoice is raised.

Visualisation

Metric Description
Import growth rate Line diagram showing last 12 months
Export growth rate Line diagram showing last 12 months

Cash Flow

Positive cash flow means that the cash inflow such as revenue covers the operating expenses in a business. Positive cash flow is therefore a useful indicator of a smoothly running business. The SBI Cash Flow metric checks the pulse of small business sector by measuring the proportion of cash flow positive businesses.

Measurement
Target concept the proportion of cash flow positive small businesses
Validity error Direct correspondence between target concept and target measure
Target measure the proportion of cash flow positive small businesses
Measurement error Invoice data entered on Xero may contain errors, which are difficult to identify and eliminate. Also, some subscribers split their accounting records and administer several orgs for the same business. These split organisational records are currently not identified and joined and are included in the metric calculation as if they represented independent businesses.
Obtained measure the proportion of cash flow positive orgs on Xero

Representation
Target set all small businesses
Frame error Xero customers represent a self-selected subset from the broader set of small businesses. The characteristics of the subset may not be in alignment with the broader population, introducing potential bias.
Accessible set small businesses on Xero
Selection error Some small businesses may be jointly represented by multiple Xero orgs.
Accessed set orgs on Xero that meet the selection criteria

Comments on measurement and representation

Some earlier analysis of Xero data suggests that actual businesses do not always have a one-to-one correspondence to an org on Xero. Some Xero users may take out several subscriptions (and thus set up separate orgs) for the same business. This is suspected to be motivated for a number of reasons: to overcome product limitations, to keep separate records for different parts of the business etc. These are probably less of a concern for the cash flow metric as these parallel orgs may balance in their own right. However, some users are suspected to split into multiple orgs based on the type of transactions they want to handle through those. For instance one org would be used for sales transactions while another org would be used for expenses.

Such split orgs can bias the SBI Cash Flow metric which rests on the assumption that all cash in and out transactions can be matched at the org level. Multiple single-sided orgs corresponding to the same real life business would be carried on toward calculating the aggregate metric as if they represented unrelated businesses thus being counted as one cash flow positive and one cash flow negative org. In this simple case their impact appears to cancel out, but this could still introduce a bias in the metric as the true cash flow position of these split-record businesses would be overlooked by the measure. Without further research into the nature of org splitting it is difficult to say if the SBI Cash Flow metric would tend to be positively or negatively biased.

Unit of Analysis

  • organisation

Data source

  • Invoice data from Xero product
  • Organisation details from XeroCard (needed for selection)
  • Custom-generated inclusion table with the list of orgs meeting the revenue criterion

Selection logic

Level Criterion Comment
Data level Use most recent version of available data
Business entity level Select every org that:
is not in trial mode paying customer as real adopter
has min. 12-month presence on Xero
uses the Business Edition of Xero
is not a practice endusers only
is not a partner end users only
is in the market of interest (e.g. UK, NZ, AU) target market only
is a Sole Trader/Company/Partnership
meets revenue criterion Under a certain revenue threshold
Transaction level Select every invoice that
affects a Bank-type account

Aggregation logic

Step Description
1. Select all eligible orgs in the given month
2. Select all eligible invoices associated with cash in and cash out transactions in the given month
3. For each org calculate total cash in by adding up the value of cash in invoices
4. For each org calculate total cash out by adding up the value of cash out invoices
3. For each org calculate cash flow position = total cash in - total cash out, flag if positive
4. Count orgs with positive cash flow

Metric calculation

Metric Description Unit
Proportion of cash flow positive small businesses For each month divide the number of cash flow positive orgs by the number of all eligible orgs considered %

Visualisation

Metric Description
% of cash flow positive small businesses Line diagram showing last 12 months

  2. Measurement refers to the path from an abstract target concept to the final edited value for a concretely defined metric seeking to capture the target concept.

  3. Representation refers to the process of identifying and selecting the objects (or units of analysis) to obtain measurements on. Similarly to measurement it considers the correspondence between an ideal (abstract) population to the actual population that gets measured.

  4. Orgs with revenue greater than 10 million NZD (for New Zealand) or 10 million GBP (for UK) over a 12-month period will be excluded. Whether an org meets this criteria is re-evaluated for each period (month). The point of this revenue cap is to impose a small business size limitation.
